:::summary
Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra (1547–1616) was the greatest writer in the Spanish language and the author of *Don Quixote* (1605/1615) — widely considered the first modern novel and one of the greatest works of literature ever written. The story of a deluded Spanish gentleman who reads too many chivalric romances and sets out as a knight-errant, accompanied by his earthy squire Sancho Panza, is simultaneously a brilliant parody of medieval romance, a profound philosophical meditation on reality and illusion, a moving portrait of friendship and idealism, and an inexhaustible comedy. Cervantes's life was marked by extraordinary hardship — slavery, imprisonment, poverty — yet he produced a work of such richness and humor that it has never been surpassed.
:::

